notesStmt.note: This illuminated and illustrated copy of the Khamsah (quintet) of Niẓāmī Ganjavī (d. 605 AH / 1209 CE) was written by Yār Muḥammad al-Haravī in 922 AH / 1516 CE. Written in four columns in black nastaʿlīq script, this manuscript opens with a double-page illuminated frontispiece signed by ʿAbd al-Wahhāb ibn ʿAbd al-Fattāḥ ibn ʿAlī. It contains thirty-five illustrations that were repainted in India during the twelfth century AH / eighteenth CE. The seal of Muḥammad Asharf ibn Muḥammad Khātam al-Ḥusaynī, dated 1173 AH / 1759-60 CE appears on fols. 1a and 401a. It is possible that the brown leather binding with center and side panels brushed with gold is original to the manuscript but was repaired at a later stage in the codex's history.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Persian.

msItem.title: Khamsah-i Niẓāmī
خمسه نظامي
msItem.incipit: بسم الله الرحمن الرحيم هست كليد در كنج حكيم...
msItem.note: Contains Makhzan al-asrār (fol. 1b), Khusraw va Shīrīn (fol. 33b), Laylá va Majnūn (fol. 121b), Haft paykar (fol. 185b), Iskandarnāmah (fol. 257b), and Iqbālnāmah (fol. 359a)

colophon.note: tammat [sic] al-kitāb al-Khamsah al-mubārak bi-ʿawn Allāh taʿālá wa-tabāraka /1/ ʿalá yad al-ʿabd al-ḍaʿīf al-mudhnib al-rājī ilá raḥmat Allāh /2/ al-ṣamad al-qawī Yār Muḥammad al-Harawī /3/ ghafara Allāh dhunūbahu /4/ m (= tamma) /5/
In Arabic; gives the title of the work and the scribe's name

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in blue, gold, and black

handDesc.handNote: Written in black nastaʿlīq script with section headings/captions in blue

decoDesc.decoNote: Thirty-five illustrations; double-page illuminated frontispiece signed by ʿAbd al-Wahhāb ibn ʿAbd al-Fattāḥ ibn ʿAlī; illuminated titlepieces with inscriptions in white ink on a decorated blue background

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated frontispiece
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illuminated frontispiece. This page begins the first poem.

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated frontispiece
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illuminated frontispiece containing two small medallions. One gives the name of the illuminator as ʿAbd al-Wahhāb ibn ʿAbd al-Fattāḥ ibn ʿAlī.

decoNote.title: Sultan Sanjar and the old woman
decoNote.note: An old woman petitions Sultan Sanjar about the questionable behavior of his policeman. The face of Sultan Sanjar was very clearly re-painted in India.

decoNote.title: Two scholars quarreling
decoNote.note: Two physicians are depicted quarreling in the presence of the king. The inscription over the doorway on the left reads: al-sulṭān al-ʿādil.

decoNote.title: Incipit with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated titlepiece introducing the second poem of the Khamsah, Khusraw va Shīrīn, which is written in white on a blue ground.

decoNote.title: Shīrīn admiring the portrait of Khusraw
decoNote.note: Shīrīn is depicted in the company of her maidens admiring the portrait of Khusraw.

decoNote.title: Khusraw watching Shīrīn bathing
decoNote.note: Shīrīn bathes in a fountain as Khusraw, drawn by her beauty, watches.

decoNote.title: Khusraw fends off an attacking lion
decoNote.note: Khusraw fends off an attacking lion.

decoNote.title: Shīrin on horseback watches Farhād
decoNote.note: Shīrin, on horseback, watches Farhād digging a canal for a stream of milk.

decoNote.title: Khusraw arriving at Shīrīn's palace
decoNote.note: Khusraw comes on horseback to visit Shīrīn, the Armenian princess.

decoNote.title: Khusraw and Shīrīn in their wedding chamber
decoNote.note: This image of Khusraw and Shīrīn in their wedding chamber has been erased at some point in the manuscript's history. The inscription on the right reads: al-sulṭān al-ʿādil.

decoNote.title: Shīrūyah stabbing his father, Khusraw
Incipit with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has a titlepiece introducing the third poem of the Khamsah, Laylá va Majnūn, which is written in white on a blue ground.

decoNote.title: Laylá and Majnūn at school
decoNote.note: Laylá and Majnūn are portrayed as small children at school, when they first met.

decoNote.title: Majnūn and his father in front of the Kaʿbah in Mecca
decoNote.note: Majnūn and his father, who is on the right, are depicted in front of the Kaʿbah in Mecca.

decoNote.title: Nawfal fighting with Laylá’s tribe
decoNote.note: Nawfal, a dedicated friend of Majnūn’s, fights with Laylá’s tribe.

decoNote.title: Majnūn, in chains, is led by the old woman to Laylá's tent
decoNote.note: A shackled Majnūn is lead by an old woman in front of the encampment of Laylá’s tribe.

decoNote.title: Majnūn playing with wild animals
decoNote.note: In the wilderness, Majnūn is comforted by wild animals.

decoNote.title: Laylá and Majnūn meeting in the palm grove
Laylá and Majnūn fainting at the sight of each other
Incipit with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has a titlepiece introducing the fourth poem of the Khamsah, Haft paykar, which is written in white on a blue ground.

decoNote.title: Bahrām Gūr killing a lion and a wild ass
Bahrām Gūr killing two lions
Fitnah carrying the ox upstairs to Bahrām Gūr
decoNote.note: Fitnah is shown carrying the ox upstairs to Bahrām Gūr. The inscription over the gate to the garden reads: Allāhu wa-lā siwāhu.

decoNote.title: Bahrām Gūr in the black pavilion
decoNote.note: Bahrām Gūr visits the princess in the black pavilion. The inscription on top reads: yā mufattiḥ al-abwāb yā musabbib al-asbāb.

decoNote.title: Bahrām Gūr in the yellow pavilion
decoNote.note: Bahrām Gūr visits the princess in the yellow pavilion. The inscriptions read: al-sulṭān al-aʿẓam al-khāqān al-aʿdal.

decoNote.title: Bahrām Gūr in the green pavilion
decoNote.note: Bahrām Gūr visits the princess in the green pavilion.

decoNote.note: Bahrām Gūr visits the princess in the red pavilion.

decoNote.title: Bahrām Gūr in the blue pavilion
decoNote.note: Bahrām Gūr visits the princess in the blue pavilion.

decoNote.title: Bahrām Gūr in the sandalwood pavilion
decoNote.note: Bahrām Gūr visits the princess in the sandalwood pavilion.

decoNote.title: Bahrām Gūr in the white pavilion
decoNote.note: Bahrām Gūr visits the princess in the white pavilion.

decoNote.note: This incipit page has a titlepiece introducing the fifth poem of the Khamsah, Iskandarnāmah, which is written in white on a blue ground.

binding.p: Brown leather with stamped center and side panels brushed with gold (no flap); inscription in upper and lower rectangles; doublures with blue dentelle-style filigree work
